4-Person Task Breakdown
Person 1 — Environment Setup + Input Parser (Min 0–1.5h)
Verify Ollama + Gemma2:2b is running locally for the whole team (ollama run gemma2:2b)

Download and save the sample data file locally

Write load_input(filepath) — reads the file, returns clean chunks the model can process

Once done, help Person 2 stress-test the model call

Person 2 — Prompt Engineer + Model Call (Min 15–3h)
Write the system prompt forcing Gemma to return only the required format (JSON for Track 2, commit message for Track 1) — no filler text

Build call_gemma(system_prompt, chunk) using Ollama's Python SDK or subprocess

This is the hardest job — test on one chunk at a time and iterate until output is consistent

Person 3 — Output Validator (Hour 1.5–3.5h)
Write validate_output(raw_text) that checks Gemma's response is properly formatted

Track 2: confirm JSON has all 4 required fields and passes json.loads()

Track 1: confirm commit message starts with a valid Conventional Commit prefix (feat:, fix:, etc.)

Handle bad/malformed output — catch errors and either retry or log the failure clearly

Person 4 (You) — Pipeline Glue + Testing + README (Hour 2.5–5h)
Wire all three functions into a single script: load_input() → call_gemma() → validate_output() → write results to output file

Make it run as one command: python main.py <input_file>

Test on a second unseen file during the edge case hour (Hour 4–5)

Write a short README with setup steps and a usage example for submission
